   "source": [
    "<h1 style=\"color: #96174e\">\n",
    "When Logic Gets Messy: Who Thinks Best Under Pressure?\n",
    "</h1>\n",
    "\n",
    "<h4 style=\"color:#0707ff\">\n",
    "Pressure\n",
    "</h4>\n",
    "\n",
    "![LLM Reasoning Graphic](image.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "<h4 style=\"color:#0707ff\">\n",
    "The Challenge\n",
    "</h4>\n",
    "\n",
    "Not all prompts are polite.  \n",
    "Some are paradoxes, traps, or puzzles that force models to *think* rather than *recite.*\n",
    "\n",
    "For this test, I gave **Gemini**, **Perplexity**, and **ChatGPT** a series of reasoning puzzles and time-sensitive logic questions — the kind that break even strong systems.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Prompt 1: “A train leaves Chicago traveling east at 60 mph…”**\n",
    "\n",
    "Classic word problem.  \n",
    "- **Gemini** calculated step-by-step but sometimes over-explained.  \n",
    "- **ChatGPT** solved it correctly, but simplified too fast.  \n",
    "- **Perplexity** looked up real-world examples of train schedules (!).\n",
    "\n",
    "It turns out: *accuracy wasn’t the point — composure was.*\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Prompt 2: “Explain this paradox in one sentence: The more you know, the less you understand.”**\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Gemini** turned poetic again, writing about humility.  \n",
    "- **ChatGPT** defined the epistemological paradox directly.  \n",
    "- **Perplexity** summarized an academic article by a philosopher named Laozi (yes, really).\n",
    "\n",
    "Each model exposed a different form of reasoning: metaphorical, logical, and empirical.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Takeaway**\n",
    "\n",
    "Testing reasoning in LLMs isn’t about who’s right — it’s about *how they break*.  \n",
    "When the logic gets messy, **style becomes signal**:  \n",
    "the poetic thinker, the rationalizer, and the fact-checker all reveal what “intelligence” really means.\n",
    "\n",
